	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>zeroone</b> [ Wed Feb 14, 2018 8:07 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>Re: NES output resolution</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Take a look at this zoom up of a Pac-Man CRT.<br /><br /><img src="https://i.imgur.com/u3U07QE.png" alt="Image" /><br /><br />It appears to have horizontal scanlines.  But, if you look closely, that effect is actually a consequence of the delta-gun shadow mask and phosphor dot layout.  In fact, the monitor is rotated 90 degrees; the electron gun is actually sweeping vertically.  I bring this up to point out that &quot;scanlines&quot; are not just the result of highly focused beams.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
